{
  "texts": [
    "Let G: L(Φ, I) → L(Φ, I) be recursively defined as follows:1. p G = ¬¬p; 2.",
    "(¬φ) G = ¬φ G; 3.",
    "(φ ∧ ψ) G = φ G ∧ ψ G; 4.",
    "(φ → ψ) G = (φ G → ψ G); 5.",
    "(□ i φ) G = ¬¬□ i φ G. ◁ Since we defined (φ ∨ ψ):= ¬(¬φ ∧ ¬ψ), we can think of (φ ∨ ψ) G = ¬(¬φ G ∧ ¬ψ G).If we simply translated □ i φ as □ i φ G, we would not get the modal extension of the famous result that φ is a theorem of classical logic iff φ G is a theorem of intuitionistic logic [Gödel, 1933, Gentzen, 1933, 1936, 1974]."
  ]
}